ng future pathways.The origins and use of conservation principles and practice from the nineteenth century to the present day are charted in this volume. Written from the perspective of a practitioner, it examines the manner in which a single, dominant mode of conservation, which held sway for many decades, is now coming under pressure from a different and more democratic heritage management practice, favouring diversity, inclusion and difference.The author blends case studies from Ireland, Cyprus and England with examples from current practice, community heritage initiatives and political policy, highlighting the development and use of international charters and conventions. Central to the main argument of the book is that the sacred cows of conservation - antiquity, fabric and authenticity - have outlived their usefulness and need to be rethought. Dr Keith Emerick is an English Heritage Inspector of Ancient Monuments in York and North Yorkshire; he is also a Research Associate at the University of York.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCultural propertyxProtectionzEngland. 0aMonumentsxConservation and restorationzEngland. 4aArchaeology & Heritage. 4aMedieval History. 4aModern History. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh  aAncient Monuments.  aAntiquity.  aAuthenticity.  aCase studies.  aConservation.  aDemocracy.  aDiversity.  aFabric.  aHeritage.  aInclusion.  aNineteenth century.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311143136940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178204266240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782042662423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782042662/original  a978-3-11-143136-9  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles